The Parliament did not support the amendment liberating Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted under an amendment to the Criminal Code.
The amendment, which would have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned Prime Minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the proposal to ease the punishment for economic crimes.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly concluding an unfavourable contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the convicted person’s appeal is due to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko called the verdict a political revenge of the regime, and the suspicion of bias in the court sparked a trial in the West.
The proposal to remove section 365 of the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs in a vote.
It needed 226 votes to pass.
