The menu of an obese child: does not eat breakfast and dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent of children being obese.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to a recent survey.
It shows once again how important it is for the healthy development of a person’s environment in which he grows up and the patterns that surround him.
For example, on the tables of obese children, sausages appear up to half as often as in families of normal-weight children.
The French fries were served for dinner the day before a study linked to an awareness campaign called Obesity Not a Coincidence by more than 19 percent of the obese.
In fat families, it is also not a habit to do sports, which is true for most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children answered that their parents at least once a week find time for active movement.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic participated in it.
It was the second year of the Obesity Not a Coincidence event, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 pupils from grades 4 to 8 have participated in the project.
Proper nutrition and sufficient exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of children who are overweight or even obese.
"For example, only half of those surveyed said they ate breakfast-lunch-lunch-lunch-dinner five times a day, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," one of the results of the study said.
No breakfast and evening sausage
Experts point out that relative details are essential for healthy development, including regular family breakfast times.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst part was finding that in a tenth of the households, there was no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are much more often consumed.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
While more than 40 percent of children surveyed regularly do sports, their parents scored less than half - 15 percent.
Make your own diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own menu according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of flour, meat and sweet dishes.
"The high popularity of sweet lemonades is particularly alarming," the study's final report said.
At lunch, the pasta just above the poultry prevailed as the main dish.
But the children practically did not like legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and noon vegetable dishes is also low.
An Approach to Health
The study also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the educational lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, in many cases there has been a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," the project results state.
This was notable, for example, for sweet lemonades, where more children would prefer ordinary water.
Children were also much more likely to tick poultry and fish as the main meal of the day and cut back on sweet foods and dumplings.
