Need for Speed: The Run races across the United States.
Recent Reviews
Originally a carefree ride, due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes, turns into a routine morning trip to the shift.
The ambition was largely fulfilled, but it is nothing if no one obviously wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run aroused high expectations before the release.
He promised to move the old racing series Need for Speed in a new direction again, and from playable demos it seemed like a game that in the genre of action racing would not have to be just in number.
We were also curious to see how the embedded passages would turn out, in which the main character gets out of the car and runs on his own.
However, as is customary in the NFS series, many things are a little different in the end than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole drags down a few unnecessary bugs that have been appearing in the series for more or less several years.
So these are not actually mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main character Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You will be driving on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea carries with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race runs on a different track and the stages are set in different, quite different and interesting environments.
It doesn’t feel like the game is always the same.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to see, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's not world-class.
But driving through the desert, autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains is visually very pleasant.
In addition, from time to time the races are varied by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught in a sandstorm, which greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you must be careful not to be overwhelmed by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well put in place.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up again (a classic duel with stopwatches) and then a duel with a single opponent awaits you.
From time to time, the police will also get involved, making your efforts even more unpleasant.
New is the passages outside the car.
It's more like an interactive animation, where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him in this way by printing the right buttons at the right moments.
It's not complicated.
Surprisingly, there are far fewer of these passages in the game than you might expect (in particular, perhaps only three).
In the end, however, it is in favor of the thing, because this element has no chance to become annoying and in the context of the above, it ranks among the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is certainly not much nowadays, but it cannot be said to be a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-packed racing here still suits the driving model quite well, even though we could find a better one in the competition.
So far, everything is in perfect order.
However, problems begin to appear after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer very good.
We do not expect this type of game to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if practically before any impact on any object you have no idea how your car will behave, then probably not all is well.
Typically, when overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, sometimes you just lick each other slightly, but sometimes in almost identical situations, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even be attacked.
Thanks to the system of restarts, it does not particularly bother, but it will detangle you reliably.
Restarts are solved so that if you break or drive far off the track, the game will throw you back to the last catch point on the track.
Only five restarts are available in each race.
When you have exhausted them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it is more of a help in case something fails, rather than that you can rely on them explicitly.
Sometimes even restarts will not help, they will be solved by the need to learn a given section of the race by heart.
The big drawback of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some corners need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply will not fit into them.
Other times you will meet at a given place "civilian" cars always in the same configuration whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see how between two opposite cars the opponent in front of you passes easily, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "calculated" so that the situation always occurs right in front of your nose.
The rivals have another advantage.
Throughout the game, you will come across several places where, again, no matter the time, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
Obviously, the enemy must get in front of you at any cost.
When it drives in front of you, it makes it worse for you to see the cars on the other side, so at first you have to smear it a couple of times.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably disgust you quickly.
And it is a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes so action-packed that sometimes you literally do not have time to watch where everything flies.
And it doesn’t matter if it’s a concept with fifty unique tracks, sorting races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas stations on the roads, because that is where you can change the car, although in most cases you can do with what you have right now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports are suitable for urban areas, strong American crashes on straight highways, and exotic supersports for technical riding, such as on winding mountain roads.
The main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common to challenges and storytelling.
To gain a higher driver level, various items are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with profile backgrounds.
At the same time, it is again connected to the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your results with other players and provides other community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you will get to the subway tunnel (bu<0xC5><0xBE>), where you run in the dark on the tracks (bu<0xC5><0xBE>).
On the tachometer, numbers between 150 and 200 km/h flash (yes) and a subway train arrives from behind and uncompromisingly knocks you down.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a few more days of discussions about whether nobody really thought a little while creating the game, or whether the authors think that we are really such idiots.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It freezes in such a way that in some tense moments the shooting decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
This is especially true of crashes with a larger number of participants, when smooth shooting would no longer be useful to you.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category "every dog is a different village" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, someone will probably not buy the game.
Need for Speed: The Run is a very good game.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS work of the last few years.
This is how the game looks unfinished.
The fun is certainly fine, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will crack you in the eyes with the power of airport headlights.
