IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally under the complex name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924, when it was originally used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous "punchers," that is, clocks recording employees' arrivals and departures.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired the supervisory board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on an invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production and sale of all sorts of machines for business - from meat slicers and cheese to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson’s leadership, the company’s turnover doubled to $9 million and began a large-scale expansion to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "peck" that set the computer standard of the time, called IBM 5150, came to the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer manufacturing to the Chinese company Lenovo, bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers, and began to fully dedicate itself to high-value-added consulting and services.
The strategy that has paid off in the last three years for IBM is the concept of Smarter Planet, the “smarter planet.”
Its goal is the smart use of technology in previously unplanned areas and the improvement of the situation, for example, in transport or urban management.
IBM recently launched the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps merchants manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history at home.
It established its branch in the then Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM Czech Republic, it also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Headquartered in Prague, Central and Eastern Europe has a world-class voice recognition research team.
