How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recreation and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the travels of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were consequently very limited.
The great paradox of the era of socialism was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually, even within the framework of socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand the queue overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (the Western currency) for a trip to the West.
By far most often, however, the Czechs spent holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs bought, and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which we no longer realize today, is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
At the end of the 1990s, the visa waiver to neighboring Western European countries was lifted, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria's Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there at least for a while.
For example, in Paris, tours of Czechs slept in tent parks, because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of travel of Czechs at this time was to transport their own food, cans, salami, etc. in order to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech koruna, which allowed our tourists to finally freely buy Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living, and with it our average wages, rose, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare trips with charter flights since 1997, which has made it incredibly cheaper for air travel thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, due to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight to exotic destinations was launched from the Czech Republic, to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm distant countries every year, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history, they spent more than CZK 15,000 per person on one foreign holiday, including the cost of stay at the place of residence.
