21st Century House in Vienna
Moved pavilion
Ingeborg Wiensowski
A story of architecture with peaks, falls and happy endings: The Austrian pavilion at the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, remained empty and vacant.
It is now being reopened as an exhibition house.
When it comes to modern post-war architecture, bright forms, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World Exhibition 1958 is a concise and famous example.
Schwanzer's pavilion received the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and lofty construction of steel and glass.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He became famous for building the pavilion of Austria for the next world exhibition.
With his legendary four-cylinder BMW Palace plus as the key to a side-building in Munich, he eventually became internationally famous in 1973.
As a temporary exhibition building, the designed pavilion after the World's Fair was placed in the Schweizer Garten near the Südbahnhof (Southern Railway Station) in Vienna, renovated and opened the Museum of the 20th Century in 1962 - it was named "The House of the 20th Century".
However, the building was not suitable for the museum, neither spatially nor technically - there were no walls for hanging art exhibits, no suitable climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art received a new booth in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and decaying more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has reconstructed the pavilion, it is now called "The House of the 21st Century" and will be used in the future as a Museum of Contemporary Art.
On Tuesday evening there will open the Museum Belvedere, to which the palace belongs, the first exhibition - a happy intention in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a graduated art historian with a distinguished career, e.g. in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum of Modernity Salzburg, vigorously promoted reconstruction among politicians and conservationists, secured public funds and private sponsorship funds, and determined the use of funds.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be exhibited by the Foundation of the same name, a café and bookstore should be created, and an office building had to be built to do so.
Strict supervision, low budget.
Krischanitz was the ideal cast to perform.
Not only did he sensitively reconstruct and enlarge the Art Nouveau buildings of Joseph Olbrich in Vienna and win the competition, but because he studied at the Technical University of Vienna with Schwanzer, and the pavilion was an "extremely important place" for him to see exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original project and also knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness when it moved to Vienna and changed its use.
There were far greater problems with the current reconstruction: the building was a “catapulte for energy,” says Krischanitz.
The profiles of the glass facade windows were replaced, fiberglass-reinforced insulating glass was used, and the glass roof was replaced with special safety glass.
Cold bridges-steel beams were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings sanitized.
Two underground floors provided a place for new use, a recessed lighting channel between the building and the street provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still a lofty Schwanzer pavilion.
The original entrance door has been preserved, the building is painted in an old anti-corrosion reddish-brown color tone.
And the cinema is still exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the monument office and a low budget.
"Often had to be found material that is good and cheap and also liked the monument office," says Krischanitz, pointing to the broken basement floor.
Despite all the pressures, problems and renovations, the building remained flexible and airy.
“It was difficult with the pavilion that came here from Brussels,” said Krischanitz, a typical “Drop-in-the-City-history.”
Such architecture, he said, is “always in the wrong place” and still wants to “awaken proper self-confidence.”
In this case, however, the House of the 21st Century is not in the wrong place, for an urbanistic happy coincidence has occurred: In the circle around the Schweizer Garten, a completely newly designed "City Quarter by the Main Station" with office and residential buildings is being created.
And perhaps there will be another happy coincidence: the house of the 21st century could receive support from another Krischanitz building, since the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle and, as they say, is already negotiating with the city about the neighborhood at the station in the Schweizer Garten.
