The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "antihistorical work".
It contains several very famous names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as rather a "book about what it was like". It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women on both sides of the barricade, from female students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and clerks.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fate, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It corrects the idea that World War I was all about the horrific trench fighting on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skilfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bee nests falling on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids, or struggling with the presence of tse-tse fly.
Almost from the beginning, it was a very touching read.
War devours people’s lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina stinking of gunpowder.
When gunfire erupts in the distance and you are a woman who is home with her children, will you run away or stay?
Who's approaching?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was unleashed.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts," said Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
Beauty and Sorrow follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from biographies, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and captivating, but thanks to the inclusion of small moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them deal with distress and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Replacements, everywhere substitutes."
"Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It refers to "meat made from pressed rice cooked in sheep fat (and supplemented with a fake bone made of wood), dried root tobacco and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles".
There were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
An American finds inner urges to savagery and brutality, and then declares about the war: "In the end, you will understand that this is human nature, not sitting in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a good book and pretending that your mask represents civilization."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
“When one finally accepts self-sacrifice, one would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “convict who is secretly hanged.”
Other remarks relate to the departure of the old Europe and the onset of new horrors.
“Conflict has increasingly become economic competition and competitive struggle,” writes Mr. Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captures what he calls “a new kind of beast of the coming century: an eloquent and ideologically sworn mass murderer in tailor-made clothes who carries out his bloodshed without getting up from the table.”
People behave completely unexpectedly, meanness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a sexually transmitted disease from prostitutes in order to avoid serving at the front.
“The most grotesque example of this behavior was the sale of gonococcal pus, which soldiers were buying and rubbing on their genitals in the hope of ending up in hospital,” she writes.
"The most desperate people would rub it in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives."
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund’s prose is quick but not pompous, which fits perfectly with his human theme.
In dozens of small outings, he captures the way the war “unleashed utterly uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.”
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books on World War I mostly worked with hints rather than complex narratives, such as Paul Fussell's "World War I and Modern Memories" or novels like Erich Maria Remarque's "Peace on the Western Front".
Mr. Englund prefers an unconventional concept.
His book has the most overwhelming ending, which is unparalleled in popular scientific literature.
But I won't tell you.
However, you will feel as if suddenly the author jumped out of the book, ripped the page from your list of heroes from your hand and set it on fire.
After a previous mistake, this time for a minute accurately scheduled raid
It was attended by hundreds of police officers, some wearing helmets used in street riots.
The night of Monday to Tuesday was chosen because by that time Zuccotti Park should be almost empty.
