The union of auxiliary workers will sue the city for dismissal
Trade unions representing hundreds of school assistants who lost their jobs last month are planning to sue the city on Wednesday, arguing that the layoffs were not necessary and, moreover, discriminatory because of the disproportionate impact on schools attended by poor students.
The court case is probably the last option left to the unions in District Council 37 in their attempt to reverse the dismissal decision.
On October 7, six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parental coordinators and other employees who were among the city’s worst-paid employees lost their jobs. Their dismissal was described by the leading union members as retaliation for the city’s failure to allow it access to a health care fund managed by the workforce last spring.
City officials categorically rejected the accusation.
At a city council meeting last month, Education Minister Dennis M. Walcott said the layoffs were part of a budget approved in June.
One of the council members immediately countered that the budget did not specifically mention the redundancies of auxiliary workers.
Representatives of District Council 37 said they had already filled out the necessary documents and warned the Department of Education that they would sue him. On Wednesday, they will convene a press conference, where they will formally announce the lawsuit before the Supreme State Court in Manhattan.
The defendants in the trial will be Mr Walcott and the Department of Education, while the plaintiffs will be eight dismissed workers, all of whom are African-American or Hispanic, as well as most of the other assistants who lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, spokeswoman for the city's legal department, said the city had not seen the lawsuit yet and would not comment on the individual charges.
According to a draft complaint filed by the New York Times, the unions targeted the number of redundancies in the city’s poorer areas to support their allegations of unfairness, arguing that poor schools have lost more assistants because they have long been denied sufficient funding.
They point out that while there were no layoffs at all in schools in Staten Island and only minimally in the Upper East Side, 17 school assistants were lost in Brooklyn, 17 in District 23 in Brownsville, and 46 in District 8 and 9 in the South Bronx.
He recalls that at Public School 36 in Harlem, five out of eight assistants lost their jobs, even though it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty. The lawsuit says: "It is not a neighborhood full of movable parents who can procure funds to offset the budget deficit."
Public School 36’s budget was cut by 3.26% this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way bonus funds were calculated for each poor student enrolled.
The unions say, among other things, that high school principals may have been confused by the way the document authorizing the dismissal of parental coordinators was written.
In the document, the word "excess" was used to describe the action, i.e. to cancel the position, although this word is much more often used to describe the transfer of a teacher from the school's payroll to the database of available workers whose salary is paid by the central authority.
“Sixty-six parental coordinators have been fired,” the complaint proposal states, “and not just moved to the database as available staff.”
The mission is over, the Congress is ready to accept the agreement on the situation in Libya
Finally, Republicans and Democrats in Congress seem to agree on something about the uprising in Libya.
But before that could happen, the revolution had to succeed, the long-running dictator Muammar Gaddafi had to be captured and killed, and the participation of United States troops ended.
On Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee will decide on a statement supported by President John Kerry (Mass.) along with Senators John McCain (Ariz.) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Conn.), in which it should congratulate the Libyans for their successful uprising and thank U.S. troops for their "statue."
