During the summer, lawmakers on both sides have been constantly arguing with each other and with the White House over the text of a series of statements to approve or reject the United States’ military role in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain unveiled a resolution authorizing the limited use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The motion was rejected in the House because of the differing views of the two political parties, so it was never even voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that the motion was rejected in the House, the Chamber also rejected measures that would stop the financing of US operations in Libya.
This put the US mission in Libya literally in a legislative purgatory – Congress criticized President Obama’s handling of the mission, but apparently did not irritate its members enough to stop supporting him in his actions.
The hesitation of Congress was eventually overtaken by other events.
The rebels captured Tripoli in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
The Senate is now ready to act.
The Commission on International Relations in its statement "congratulates the people of Libya for their immeasurable courage and admirable perseverance in their efforts to liberate their people" and "praises the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their allies who have engaged in the operation to protect the Libyan population, for their extraordinary bravery and professionalism."
The statement also "reaffirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya."
Will the new proposal receive the full support of the Commission for International Relations, or will the legislators again be split in two, as was the case when the proposal was approved in June?
