Mr Lugar's spokesman said Monday he had not yet seen the final version of the new proposal.
The House will vote this week on an amendment to the Constitution that would require a balanced budget, which should be the highest legislative priority for almost all Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
This measure, pushed by Bob Goodlatte (Va.), will be the first amendment to the Constitution on a budget or other topic to be voted on by the entire House or Senate.
The other legislators, despite considerable efforts, have not yet managed to push their proposals to the vote itself.
Goodlatt's proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the Constitution that were introduced in Congress and touched on a wide range of different topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal submitted to the House and the Senate - and others are just minor variations of others.
In the House alone, you can find at least 15 versions of the balanced budget amendment and another handful that would like to “regulate federal spending.”
Some of the proposals are identical, but their proponents — especially aspiring Republicans who want to improve their reputation — can boast of their “authorship.”
The budget regulation decree, which was approved in August, required both the House and the Senate to vote on an amendment to the balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favor of a non-binding statement in support of the creation of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, several members want to discuss limiting the number of periods in which members of Congress can serve, while José E. Serrano (N.Y.) wants to increase the number of periods in which he can serve as president.
Representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) offered a range of supplements that would, among other things, guarantee the right to quality education and medical care.
The amendment banning same-sex marriage and the amendment banning the burning of the national flag remain a permanent proposal.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be repealed if two-thirds of states oppose them.
Although members of Congress seem to be very active in proposing various amendments, they do not deviate significantly from the average in comparison with previous years.
In the 111th Congress, they proposed 77 amendments, while in the 100th Congress there were 66.
Their activity even pales in comparison to the early 1990s, when, according to the Senate Library’s statistics, members offered more than 150 additions every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than the current politicians.
The last amendment, the 27th Amendment, was ratified in 1992, but was actually proposed by Congress in 1789.
