Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Explore You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man presenting his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July murderous rage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realised it wasn’t really that hard to find them,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The amount of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says, that it was enough for scientists to simply use advertising on the site to identify the demographics they were looking for with absolute accuracy - something that marketing staff have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, then turned their attention to them and sent them ads. However, instead of using them to invite them to a newly formed group or offer them some dietary products, they encouraged them to fill out a questionnaire about their own future, their relationship to violence and optimism.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are angered by rising immigration rates.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and policy researchers use this site to study everything from health problems to social trends hiding behind status updates, posts on walls, and pressed “Like” buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them provides on average three different data per day, which makes this social network literally an "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic papers, in the name of which the word Facebook occurs, has increased from the state five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the ability to study people without having to harass them somewhere on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to do a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side where they'd never let you go," says Bartlett.
"Facebook breaks all this down - you just go straight to them."
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify a socio-health problem and avoid it.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken outings on Facebook were much more at risk for alcoholism than students who remained silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that peers of students monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
“The problem can’t be solved if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise have no chance of discovering."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The information team of the site has compiled statistics on the relationship between the relationship statuses and Valentine's Day, the 2010 election turnout and the nation's satisfaction rate (mainly using the information to which they had access - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available for research and others).
But Facebook users know that the page is following them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, you need to provide the site with your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clear rules on how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most users would have thought that scientists could look into their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using his students’ public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it that the information was only between them and their friends."
The question of methodology is also to be considered.
Even when researching off-line, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to verify how much of the information on the profile and the posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, believes that the pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool to use in research.
“When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” she says.
“Social research should be about society and social activities – and a hell of a lot of social activities are still taking place offline.”
