7 Lessons From A Lost Interview With Steve Jobs In A Movie Going To Cinema This Week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, opinions began to emerge from people who compared him to Henry Ford – and elected him for his genius the Greatest Modern Inventor.
Jobs’ recently rediscovered interview, which was dusted for a special film headed to theaters this week, will feature the fact for all Apple fans that his creative mind perfectly understood the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer and a self-appointed member of the hippie movement, but also a meticulous organizer and a man who fits every little thing into the smallest detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer from "the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work... [but] between a great idea and a great result product is still a long way to go."
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on the TV show The Triumph of Computer Fools, which discussed the dawn of personal computers. During the filming, a unique, more than an hour long interview took place.
By that time, it had been ten years since Jobs was forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company NeXT, eagerly anticipating how the general public would accept the Internet.
Only a short portion of Cringely's entire interview was eventually used in the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transit.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
It is this material, slightly edited, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which heads to selected theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is notorious for his reluctance to give longer interviews, Jobs is surprisingly excited to be able to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
He also appears to be a very thoughtful person.
Four times during the interview, there is a longer pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when you see how Jobs thinks through the answer perfectly to be as concise and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, when he acts impatiently on Cringely’s questions and pushes him to get to more important problems and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, and it brings up terribly prophetic ideas as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right and wrong, while offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about Jobs, whom we see here as an eager dreamer in the heyday of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
It did not take long, and after he had expressed his ideas, he also began to put them into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from The Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How to learn to run a business:
“Over the years of business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing this?’ and the answer was always the same: ‘Well, that’s just how it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, never thinking deeply about things related to business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues by describing his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way the costs were recorded - they often started with the inscription "standard costs", he could only guess about their amount. At that moment, he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine the business costs within a moment.
How he made a snapshot of the pope:
Jobs recalls the “Blue Box” he built with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make free calls to anywhere in the world.
There has been a lot of talk about the device in the past, but Jobs’s enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the device using a paid phone and switched from one AT&T network to another while using as many satellites as possible.
“At least half a dozen times we’ve been around the world like this, so when we yelled at a pay phone, it came a minute later from the second phone at the door,” Jobs laughs.
“We were young and found that we could build something that could run billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us made a tiny thing that could control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience and I think Apple would never have existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a joke he and Wozniak almost made to the end. Through the Blue Box in the middle of the night, they called the Vatican and asked if they could talk to the Pope, impersonating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Gradually, high-ranking members of the Catholic Church were summoned to speak to an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and only just before they woke up the Pope himself to the phone did the couple giggle and put the phone down.
How he fell in love with technology (and telephoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 years old and was looking for spare parts to build an odometer, he found Bill Hewlett's number in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute interview, Jobs had secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a CRT monitor, and I immediately fell in love with it.
As a teenager, I was progressing higher and higher in HP, hanging around that computer and starting to write programs for it.
How to innovate:
In several places, Jobs talks during an interview about how he invents new products on the go.
At the beginning of his career, when he went to sell a pair of printed circuit boards, one customer asked him to assemble a whole computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days, during which he had to invent, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
When he was later at Apple, he recalled the problems they faced in developing computer mice:
“I remember when we were arguing quite wildly... yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] until I stopped having fun, I went out and found a designer.”
Ninety days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies are taking their breath away:
Long before he led Apple’s resurrection, Jobs foresaw that many industry leaders would stumble and lose market share in their vision.
"Let's say you work for IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
At that point, sales and marketing are already dominating, so companies are headed by people who are in charge of just that, while people who are in charge of their own products are out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that led the company to its unshakable position is now being replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
This is exactly what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned virtually the entire computer industry.
It could have been 10 times bigger than it is, it could have been Microsoft in the 1990s...
Instead of winning, they lost.
How innovation is a form of art:
“There’s still a long way to go between a great idea and a great result product... and as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
During this time, you will learn a lot about him.
You have to make a number of compromises - certain things just electrons, glass, robots or factories do not force you to do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind – different concepts – and put them together...
At the end of the day, it’s all about taste — you try to think of the best things that humanity has ever created, and in a certain way you try to translate them into what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
The Macintosh company was so amazing and successful because the people who worked there were great musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians and, coincidentally, the best computer experts in the world.
Without computers and new technologies, they could do amazing things in completely different industries.
Scalia and Thomas were having dinner with opponents of the Healthcare Act while their case was in court.
