How to Recognize a Lie
A quick look at recent headlines shows how serious and ubiquitous lies and deception are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy accusing him of sexually harassing several women -- both sides claim the other is lying.
Penn State University administrators were accused of perjury when they tried to hide records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling U.S. President Barack Obama with his microphone down that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie was able to destroy entire careers and engulf the stability of many countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately disproved by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misusing campaign funds to try to cover up his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that raged around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual affair with Monica Lewinsky.
There's stories of cheating in school and at university.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make them look good in their reviews.
Mentors who are supposed to teach the opposite send the message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many frauds do we face?
Studies show that in a single day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first meeting.
Determining lies, or “recognition of lies,” is an essential skill that everyone should learn, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar to, say, Sharad, when a person shouts: "I have you." Deception recognition is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been disproved.
The liars look you in the eye.
It’s not like they’re stuttering, stuttering, blushing, or stitching.
However, do not assume that it is somehow difficult to spot and expose the liars.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from the sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I’ve spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from the vast and evolving lie-recognition industry, and it’s clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can help you a lot in today’s complex world – especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or leading people.
Good liars can read others well, let them relax in their vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "focused on others" lies - mostly to protect one's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (although the lies they tell are mostly "horrific").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called "initial observation."
Thanks to him, he will later find out what to compare with.
Notice the body posture of the subject, his laughter, work with the voice.
You should know if someone is constantly tapping their feet so as not to unjustifiably accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
