Court Approves ‘End of Analog Broadcasting’ in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuit filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which wants to expedite the so-called "off analog signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. It noted that the necessary eight votes were not found, which would invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued a decree outlining the individual steps that will lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed on the ground that the qualified majority of eight votes needed to enable the court to comment on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the said decree, which thus remains valid, had not been reached.
The draft judgment drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero presents the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of all issues related to radio and television is a matter that is reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunication Commission (Cofetel), thus violating the principles of hierarchical subordination and exception to the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an attempt to fight the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all the actions described in it, leading to the transition to digitalization.
The ministerial meeting also decided to reject the motion filed by the House of Representatives, without entering into a discussion on the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general standards measures to prepare public administration.
"I don't think that even if she did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has experienced in recent years. It is associated with better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would mean delaying the benefits of digitalisation, which requires a decision in the public interest, because digitalisation has not only a technical dimension, but also "affects economic, social, political and national security issues".
As he stressed, these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state. It includes a number of competences that the Constitution entrusts to the hands of the government of the state".
He recalled that a number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to the digital system and have done so through their governments, even though they had highly specialized technical bodies at their disposal.
He said it was not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree that to some extent interfered with the powers of Congress, to introduce compliance with laws prepared by the legislative power into the area of administration.
