The quintet included the country in its tour to celebrate 20 years of existence
“A trip to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality.”
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We’ve been waiting for over 20 years, but the band itself assures us that for them the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively with Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on tour in South America to celebrate their 20th anniversary and will make a unique stop in Central America on Sunday the 20th.
This day will be played from 7:30 p.m. at the National Stadium with the angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from an interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the website of La Nación on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is also our dream, which is becoming a reality.
We are barely a second time in South and Central America and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a beautiful country and I hope we can stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally love the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your biggest supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people even refer to the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have come about in a matter of weeks.
We’ve done some great shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that puts us in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing to Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. So we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
Looking at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played here, we have no limits on what we can’t do.
We will try to perform the best possible show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why? Hmm?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose what songs we’re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have already forgotten about it.
That makes the show more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of art.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, I'm sure you do.
First of all, I think that none of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years.
We are aware of how much has been given to us and we are touched that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are fortunate to have the opportunity to visit the places we have always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the emergence of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the greats themselves are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of that and we are honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with others.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we're all lucky to still be in this world, and secondly, the fact that we're constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open musical pathways that give everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other’s music, and I don’t think it could have been better.
Your relationship to the word glory has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for the music, you remember that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You must not get carried away by being famous, rock stars. Neither of us ever really cared about this.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs, and at the beginning it was something spectacular.
As a band we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him, about him, about him, it was always a joy to work with him
He was an incredible person and I miss him so much.
National band Las Robertas will be commissioned to open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why you chose them as forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several designs and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious about what Las Robertas will offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could spend the whole evening talking about bass players that I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it was out of fashion?
I think we've all always felt lightly separated from the word grunge.
When I say grunge, I imagine the bands that I've mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if that kind of music is still valid today, it's something great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music than ever before.
In the beginning, your music was slightly gloomy, and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there are a few songs on the new album that are lighter to beat, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and the songs are deeply dark.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs are just that for me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
