Fujimori hospitalized for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is currently under medical control.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told TV channel Canal N that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases in three days, where they should find out why he is in pain and why he is losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said he believed Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself did not want the pardon because he felt innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and to these problems were added other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving a sentence at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a killing squadron of troops operating illegally during the first years of his reign.
Mujica visits Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday, aiming to expand trade between the two nations and touch on political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of a large-scale visit full of meetings with representatives of the Uruguayan community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan Presidential Office.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political matters between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on the list of tax havens at a G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that will continue to remain in the position of tax havens will be excluded from the international community, a statement that provoked a negative stance on the part of Uruguay and a consultation with the ambassador to this European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the world’s most powerful emerging and developed countries. Since January this year, it has had an information exchange agreement with the Latin American country to prevent double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to concretize fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)'s "black list" of countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of cooperation in the field of taxation.
From a trade point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have concluded a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has strengthened the exchange of goods between the two countries.
Bearded plumber runs in 3D thanks to "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for more than 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the villain Bowser, but has never yet appeared in 3D: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
