Colom Approves Portillo's Extradition to the United States
President <0xC3><0x81>lvaro Colom said on Tuesday that he has taken steps to extradite former President Alfonso Portillo, who is accused of plotting to launder $70 million in the United States.
This is the end of a process aimed at getting Guatemala to respond to a request from a northern country demanding the extradition of Portillo in order to be able to prosecute him.
At a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was in line with the independence of the judiciary and the executive branch and that he remembered that the criminal court had already ordered his extradition.
He assured that during his term of office he had “not interfered” in court decisions and allowed all extraditions that came to his desk.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and personal injury, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's move marks a step of execution after all judicial and constitutional instances were exhausted to lead the trial against the former president, who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and human rights have been guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of embezzlement of $120 million by the Department of Defense during his presidency, a process preceded by extradition, but the Department of Public Affairs appealed, bringing the case back into play.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people in a state of emergency
The organization was created to help children without education not to find themselves on the margins of society.
The balance sheet of the first 25 years of the Trinijove social support organization is very important: 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion have been helped. The organization has been helping them to overcome difficult situations for 25 years.
To this must be added the long hundred jobs that have been created for this social group.
Yesterday’s anniversary also served to present the balance sheet as part of a ceremonial act that took place in the former production premises of the Fabra i Coats factory and which was attended by more than 300 people.
Trinij’s organization was founded in the Trinitat Vella district in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with low education, without a job, struggling with drug addiction or in a situation where they could fall into social exclusion.
Yesterday’s meeting in Sant Andreu was attended by a large number of representatives of organizations and institutions that have cooperated with the association over the past 25 years.
Various political representations, at the time of the elections, showed the unified nature of the work carried out by Trinij.
Along with Generalitat President Arthur Mas and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, former socialist education adviser Ernest Maragall and former deputy mayor and current environmental socialist councillor Ricard Goma attended the ceremony.
The current Social Welfare and Family Advisor, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of Social Work at La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also visited the large hall of Fabra i Coats.
Mas said that Trinius was created in a very difficult time and that today also presents a number of obstacles, but added that the work that the association has brought to this day is "a good foundation".
The president cited Trini as an example of how one can fight against adverse circumstances and how to give courage to people in difficult situations.
"The crisis is nothing new for this organization and for the work it does," he said.
There was a eviction of the occupied house, where gigantic parties were held
Aliens seized 11 of the 13 apartments in the building in Balmes, 51
Twelve occupants left the house at noon yesterday without resistance.
All indications are that the nightmare experienced by the neighbors of number 51 on Balmes Street is finally over.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they were illegally occupying yesterday at noon, where they held gigantic parties that woke up neighbors. They left the building by court order and without police intervention.
After the operation, the lock on the door was replaced to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded," the warden said.
The occupiers, who seized 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all electrical and partially water equipment, painted the walls and left trash of all kinds, especially alcoholic beverage cans.
In the first three apartments there were huge parties that lasted up to two days and woke up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that while the building was occupied, sales fell by 80%.
The owner of the discotheque stresses that the occupiers of the building were unfair competition to her, because they sold drinks for 3 euros, while the discotheque costs 10.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment business had to respond to the lawsuits of the neighbors because of the noise. However, the problems were caused not by the visitors of the disco, but by the residents of the occupied house and especially those who participated in the parties organized here, the frequency and intensity of which has increased in recent weeks, according to the angry residents of the neighborhood.
The owner of the disco explained that the problems were so great that she even agreed with the owner of the building and for nine months she forgave her rent.
Police have also confirmed that they have received more complaints from neighbours over the past few weeks.
Alberto Fernández Díaz, chairman of the PP People's Party's City Group at the town hall, last week demanded that "the building be immediately evicted to end the problems of civil coexistence that neighbours are suffering and the destruction of the area".
The chairman of the People's Party explained that only one floor had been seized before the summer, but in recent months, the occupiers had reached all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in one of them even thefts had occurred.
In this regard, he added that "impunity must be ended and there must be consistency when it comes to acts against civil responsibility that took place in the building".
Yesterday, the city police also evacuated a building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police reached building 35 on Mont-ral Street after being summoned by neighbors who saw four people entering the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
The park or the mountains?
The architects met on the occasion of the announcement of the procedure, which carries more than a controversy about fees
The city's 16-gate competition reopens the debate on the role of the Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the already extinct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park of the metropolitan city of Barcelona.
What's more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
After the CMB disappeared in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper boundary of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that do not orient themselves on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of the Yogi bear.
This was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, records more of the idea of the park.
Either that, or someone's trying to place a gate in the field.
The only question is: Collserola, the park or the mountain?
During the competition, both from the point of view of purely organizational and on the basis of reflection on the city, this issue becomes the central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It is a subject as clear as when two members of this old caste of the elect shake hands when they meet in an elevator.
And it was this achievement that sparked one of the rare convergences between what three Barcelona architects and leading university professors think.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is well-founded.
According to Roldán, after the issue of the Gulf Party began, "it is necessary" to discuss the "mountain side" as well, so that Ildefonse Cerd's speech on green apples was not finalized.
"We have to start from the principle that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its great availability.
Collserola is more complex," said the architect, for whom the name "Gateway to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we must not imagine them "as entrances to the park, but rather as demarcations of zones where it is possible to operate".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona, with experience in the world of urbanism, qualifies the proposal as an “intellectual challenge” posing “some dangers”.
The danger stemming from the “uncertainty that the public space project presents today” after the experience of the 1980s, which had its “swan singing” in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very definition of the boundaries where it should be built.
"To define something is to take the next step," that is to say, in principle, to go one step further.
“We need to keep in mind the new urban and planning tools, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster.”
If we look at the question in more detail, Modol believes that the valley slope of Collserola can be "considered a park", but not the Barcelona part, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also reminded that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola, which "must not end up in a dump", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his office to intervene in the project from the "first moment".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of pass that allows architects to engage in the debate, but he "doubts" that it should be this very technical profile that will lead multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills", he adds) to create: "Architects should be just tools".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the game its name is complex because Collserol’s global vision is missing in the tender documents: “There have been 16 tenders announced covering the entire mountain-sea axis, but there is no longitudinal study that looks at the area and understands it as a whole.”
This causes that at least he, applied to all 16 selection procedures.
Otherwise, the design of one gate may encounter the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
In his view, the City Hall should guarantee that the zone immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide a full-length zone of equipment to ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
Casino has pardoned Jonas Larrazabal, who will be released
After 72 days of imprisonment, Cadino Red granted pardon to Mayor Monterrey's brother in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged blackmail.
Manuel Jonas Larrazabal spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after Casino Red’s legal representative granted him a pardon before the Second Criminal Court in the district, which was dealing with a blackmail case in which Mayor Monterrey’s brother was charged.
After the Casino Royale assassination, Casino Red owner Sergio Gil García published a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonas was supposed to ask him to pay an economic quota to allow Monterrey City Hall to operate illegally at the betting house.
After the public prosecution, the State Prosecutor's Office began prosecuting the brother of the panist mayor. On September 2, he was detained and imprisoned for 30 days.
After 4 hours spent in front of Public Ministry Agent No. 3 for Property Crimes, he was transferred to Prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo in the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days after the second detention order was issued and an agent of the Public Ministry denied the possibility of complicity or organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the criminal court in Cadereyta on suspicion of blackmailing the owners of Casino Red in the amount of one and a half million pesos. However, he remained only a few hours in a moderately supervised prison because he was threatened with death.
The leaders allowed him to remain in the city cells in San Nicolás de los Garza during the trial.
On 25 October, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the Secretary of the Second Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who stated that after almost two months of investigation, sufficient evidence had been gathered to prove Jonas's guilt. Among the evidence, for example, the payment of an amount of 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the casino in exchange for a promise that the operation would be allowed.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, presented himself to Judge José Luis Pecin and asked for a pardon for the brother of the mayor of the region. On the basis of this, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During a legal hearing with the representative of the Public Ministry assigned to this court, Ramiro Arias, asked García Gómez whether the damage had been repaired and which of the partners had decided to grant the pardon, but the lawyer made it clear that the name would remain confidential.
On the basis of the official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal. In the trial conducted against him, no complaint can be filed. Also, it is not possible to apply for compensation for damages or punishment.
After a hearing with a legal representative at around 15:50, the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazabal Bretón.
The secretary of the court, Jorge Yanez, arrived at the prison in San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonas that he had been granted an official pardon and his case had been postponed to the archives.
He also informed him that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gave details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) said the results of an investigation into the crash that killed government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven others showed the helicopter landed directly on the ground with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, said the pilot had noted before the takeoff that the climatic conditions of the flights allowed.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings entangled in the branches of trees 25 meters from the place where the unit lost its hull."
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, so it met all the requirements for the transportation of personnel.
In addition, he said that on the basis of the investigation carried out in the impact area, no parts were found on the ground.
"The search revealed that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft collided with the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all the requirements for the carriage of passengers.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that the most important thing at the moment is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation can take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the moment of impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascent terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a normal overflight operation," he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome listed six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in AICM indicate adequate conditions at takeoff, accordingly, the aircraft is moving towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility as far as the Cuernavaca Valley.
The location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the helicopter from the radar match, it is likely that before the impact there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of aircraft residues in a restricted area:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and sideways.
A sketch of the dispersal of the plane's remnants indicates that the helicopter was intact at the time of the impact on land.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene to suggest that there had been an explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the fieldwork, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloping, the height of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show images in which there was probably a decay along the aforementioned route.
The information provides elements that seem to suggest that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground at several locations.
After a careful search of the area surrounding the accident, in an area that is larger than the area of demarcation, no remains of the helicopter were found, which reinforces the assumption that the collision occurred in a state when the helicopter was still intact.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has started research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research with the aim of discovering the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene causing obesity in children and young people. The research entitled "The Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents" will allow to obtain results regarding overweight.
In a report, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Biochemistry Research Unit at the 21st Century National Medical Center Specialized Hospital, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public can also participate in the research, whether they are authorized or not. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where tests for minors will be carried out from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico) and since October 8, this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East of Mexico).
Once the data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to track down risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) are made to all participants, blood pressure is measured, the level of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin is determined, and genes are examined (it tries to identify genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects health workers’ concerns about the alarming increase in children’s weight.
