There will be no asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
If tiles were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 splinters after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavements were possible, there would be consequences.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Bursts, delivered in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should create a mixture with similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of ditches.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others with a low molecular weight, called maltenes. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but varies during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, noted a chemical engineering expert.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible tiles, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Between the topmost layers there is an asphalt liner, consisting of small stones watered in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the liner is watered with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible that the forces in the pavement are well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, a chemical engineer believes.
He added that on the asphalt liner is placed the last layer called a shell, formed by fine stone, that is, sand also poured in the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have a greater mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must ensure friction on the road.
Since it will be subjected to a heavy load as part of the paving, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken of the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great impact on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is moist, the water spreads inwards and it is difficult to get out, this causes the softening of all the layers of the tile and thus the formation of burrows.
He explained that during the formation of the burrows, the film of the shell is first damaged and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage does not occur in one moment, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in the formation of ditches, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tiles must correspond to the load on vehicles and must ensure that this load is not exceeded. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent occurrence of ditches.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that we still have a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt and the research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair ditches without having to use high temperatures.
