This was the work of a Cali resident who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano.
A fingerprint expert from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, last year, a fingerprint expert from CTI in Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of Farc’s supreme leader: “Alfonse Cana,” by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working at the CTI department this week, one was Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in forensic research for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked at the Chocó City Hall, where he often had to break through the forest for more than five days in order to get to the place where there were corpses that needed to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital, Valle, and after completing the relevant courses, he began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of skin friction, i.e. palms of hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against the aforementioned Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to bring clothes for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
He left for Cauca on Friday night in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he would have to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to take a card with Guillermo León Sáenz's fingerprints (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigating team at the place where the corpse was, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But prints don't lie.
Along with the galton magnifying glass, ink and transplanter, and light, Eliazar began to compare the dactyle records of the corpse with those of the card.
His eyes did not disappoint him: he was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, a Puerto Tejada man was commissioned to confirm to the Secretary of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, whether he really was the supreme commander of the Farc.
Searching for tracks
The recognition given to Eliazar González by President Juan Manuel Santos at the press conference of the Operations Service against "Cano" is very significant for the dactyloscope from Siín de Cali.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, which can play a key role in deciding crimes.
In addition to identifying corpses, these people assist in the investigation of crimes such as theft or murder, and confirm the identity of the persons caught.
When they are caught, many delinquents present false papers or have no papers at all.
We'll take their fingerprints and search the database.
The investigator said that in the case of injuries, he had to remove a piece of the house wall in the house, because in this place the thief leaned to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not designed to take fingerprints, but in this case we were able to get a full handprint and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts,” he said.
Fingerprints can also confirm or disprove suspicion in the case of murder.
Recently, they found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
Based on the investigation, it was determined that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder, and the print on the bottle indeed confirmed it.
Although it is not 100% possible to confirm that he was indeed the murderer, it is obvious that he appeared on the scene of the crime.
The CTI’s fingerprint expert explained that the objects are “wiped off using chemical or physical reactive substances.”
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to collect them.
After that, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, which is a database of delinquents, or to the Registratur.
“The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians out there today whose data is not recorded anywhere,” the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as it appears in the CSI television program.
Just like everything that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch leaves traces.
However, if it can be used, an appropriate comparison must be made.
