Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a theme that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balance sheets or under emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural for an election meeting to be an opportunity to think about such deposits and the place that the energy from the core occupies.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the options proposed are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
So far, there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic developments will cause a doubling of electricity demand by 2050 if we do not want to deprive a significant part of the world’s population of an important part of life.
At the same time, there will be a lack of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity, while not forgetting the essential need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a topic that is currently disappearing from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
But this is not the case in Belgium, which subordinates its decision to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor Switzerland, which it considers right to build only the last generation of power plants.
On the contrary, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, continue their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by resuming the construction of one power plant that was interrupted after the disaster at Three Mile Island.
If the German model based on renewable energy is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts this.
Berlin’s choice will result in higher electricity prices, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European champion in wind power, from which it consumes 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularity, which is why CO2 emissions and Danish electricity prices are 65% or 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbors will pay the electricity bill 40% higher than the payment of French households.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of keeping industry on national territory, French businesses benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful declarations about the re-industrialisation of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
The price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, just as they do not fundamentally oppose this energy, as opinion polls show.
Recall that our country’s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 follow-up jobs.
A strong exporting sector is attracting a large number of SMEs to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France decides to leave the core, it would sacrifice a considerable number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose the 6 billion euros a year that the country receives for its exports of nuclear facilities and services.
What power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to run for 60 years while its manufacturer’s bankruptcy was planned?
In solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magical source for energy production, indeed, that there is no diabolical one.
The development of low-CO2 plants, nuclear plants and renewable energy plants by the French industrial group AREVA demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is absolutely necessary to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the State Nuclear Safety Authority, which exercises uncompromising and transparent oversight over existing nuclear power plants as well as over the construction of a new power plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in their blood.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island to have taken place under normal operating conditions, with no human casualties and no environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the concepts of the reactor and the inexcusable human errors caused the drama.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this disaster as it did from the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers is that the EPR reactor is a concept capable of resisting such phenomena.
