Paris is concerned about ties between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-standing suspicions that there are links between the Al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (AQMI) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even admitted that Algeria had "become certain" of this from now on.
“The way the two organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that there is a great deal of cooperation between them,” he explained without further elaboration.
Paris seems to have similar analyses.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two French men in Niger in January 2010 could help illuminate the interconnection bridges.
After being abducted by AQMI members from a restaurant in Niamey, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time as several of their abductors in an operation carried out by French special forces.
French and Nigerian investigators were to find several phones with chips belonging to the terrorists in the rubble.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the calls made leads to several people in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers: one leads to a Nigerian who has long resided in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria that is the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man said to be close to AQMI and the sect.
“It’s progress, but there’s no doubt we need to wait for more compelling evidence before we start talking about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
