Nord Stream, the new entry port of Russian gas to Europe
The long-distance Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has started to work.
It must supply gas equivalent to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have jointly turned the control valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will flow to Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is equivalent to the total French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline of the gas pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction has the character of a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being transported by land by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, the two countries are losing a bit of power: the possibility of pushing Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
That is to say, it is a politically sensitive subject.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained more certainty in its purchases.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project has created rifts between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Just five years ago, Russia succeeded in pursuing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy, high-gas Western states, whose deposits are coming to an end.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us,” François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the point at which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The subsea pipeline is made of steel and is fitted with a concrete casing to protect it from the anchors of sea vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid minefields from the period of World War II.
“For security reasons, nearly a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which on its entire length is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations.
A control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project managers rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see the Russian state company permanently settle off their coasts.
"In the event of a malfunction, we stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will leak into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders, because the welds were designed to leak once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is checked from the outside by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is checked by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed with gas.
At the end of the three-day journey at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish line.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake, remains in the lead.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom then leased all of its gas transportation capacities to the company for a five-year contract that could be renewed.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works should reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment cost rose to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves are 4.5 meters high and form the gas exit gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
Moleskine - branded notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded fifty years ago, wants to once again provide the pleasure of writing.
It brings the scent of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and by its leaves of stale white color as if aged over time.
The Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, at that time decided to launch a new design, but differentiated notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, undertakes the launch of a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (skin imitation), which is used, for example, for surface treatment of benches.
This type of notebook was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has brought back an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand’s leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from the secret production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create an artificial portrait of the buyer, as the notebook will appeal to the businessman as well as the student or professionals.
Moleskine’s notebook image includes that its owners are people cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, now has almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to bookstores and through the FNAC chain of shops to small boutiques in the heart of towns and cities, where he has been able to assert his identity.
“We followed the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, through the turbulent development of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition "Zacházka", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also released new records of a notebook reminiscent of a leopard.
Moleskine profits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases ... The brand is expanding to a wide range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment funds SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today's the opening of the 15th Disability Employment Week.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed persons with disabilities is twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% versus 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
"No, underlines Éric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Week for the Employment of the Disabled."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be said that for the unemployed disabled people, numerous obstacles remain before their entry to work.
These are older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a high school diploma and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very prevalent: 53% for the disabled versus 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that particularly complicate the return to work and that are the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the Tremplin Association, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective braking.
There are unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by IMS-Entrepreneurre pour la Cité found that managers surveyed had "poor knowledge of disabled persons" with "excessive knowledge of persons in a wheelchair and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the 6% disability target set by the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, which date from 2008, indicate a state equal to 2.6%.
“We’re now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization tasked with levying fees on businesses that don’t comply with the law.
The evidence is the number of "fined" businesses, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 guilty businesses to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, put strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
